<font color="#FF0000">IN-COUNTRY OUT PROCESSING</font><br>
<tt>Wed Jan 22 20:17:46 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tanya, the unique thing that I discovered about Vietnam was that you could have six vets in a room and if they were talking about their tours; it usually sounded like six different wars.  I talked to a vet in my &quot;group&quot; who was in-country, in my old unit, six months after I came back. It was like we were talking about two completely different wars.  <br>
When I was in-country my unit was with the 1st Air Cav in the Central Highlands. My friend, in the same unit, six months later; was attached to the Americal Div.  He spent most of his tour on the coast around Chu-Lai.  My two tours was in An Khe in the mountains.  Same experience just a world apart.<br>
I guess the point is that most experiences are personal.  The views are based on cultural, religious, and family values.  This war and the vets are effected by their value system and the way we processed the things that we experienced.<br>
Well, I will end this by saying that this my feelings. I do not speak for any other vets.. This is just the way that I processed it.
